column12: Ohm's Law and Kirchhoff's Law are the foundation of circuit analysis. These principles explain how voltage, current, and resistance relate to eachother.
The principles behind Series and parallel circuits are different. Each individual type of circuit structure reacts differently with respect to the voltage, current, and resistance.
Series and parallel combination circuits are important in order to understand electronics. This topic teaches how to analyze these circuits in order to obtain the critical information.
Filters are common in electronics, so it is important to understand them. This topic goes over how filters affect the input signal as well as what circuit components make up a filter.
The subject matter that relates to PN Junctions has information about the fundamental operation of diodes. Doping, conductivity, and how this allows a diode to operate will be discussed here.
This topic teaches how rectifiers work and how diodes, as well as AC and DC sources relate to them.
The power supply, or source voltage, carries information in a signal waveform. The previous subject of rectifier circuits will help in the understanding of this power supply topic.
Diode limiter and clamper circuits interact with the input signal to give a different output. In this topic, the student will learn how this is done.
The information in this topic covers Zener diodes and how they are different from other types of diodes. Also, we will discuss how a Zener diode can act as a regulator.
Transistors are the cornerstone of electronics. The different terminals of the transistor as well as all the seperate modes are explained here.
Common emitter is a specific type of amplifier. Certain conditions as well as some circuit elements
This topic goes over common collector amplifiers. This type of amplifier is non-inverting.
A third type of amplifier is common base. This amplifier is unique in that the base is shared.
Multistage amplifiers are important. In this topic, you will learn why they are useful for impedance matching.
This topic teaches you how a push pull amplifier works as well as how distortions and harmonics can be reduced.
